2024-06-04 10:35;PMODILAY;[~NLU3] actually, I looked into the codebase and see readdir usage in other apps so the problem might be not in readdir in particular but simply leakage of memory in your case since you don't use closedir() in ./src/filedump_handler.cpp  IterateDirectoryHelper() 

In docs we can read: _You can call readdir() repeatedly to list all of the entries contained in the directory specified by the pathname given to opendir(). {*}You must call [closedir()|https://www.qnx.com/developers/docs/7.1/com.qnx.doc.neutrino.lib_ref/topic/c/closedir.html] to c{*}lose the directory stream and free the memory allocated by opendir()._

 ;;;

column691:
2024-06-04 10:57;NLU3;[~PMODILAY]  Yes, we also found that we did not call closedir.

The issue could be completely solved by invoking the ‘closedir’ function if the read dir is not a shared memory path. But we tested and found that even if we invoked the ‘closedir’ function, the problem was not completely solved, this is because the dir we intend to read is /dev/shmem, which is a shared memory path. 

This is what we found: before invoking 'closedir', if one app crashes, the added heap memory will be 224kb, if another app crashes, another 224kb will be allocated. After invoking 'closedir', if one app crashes, the added heap memory will be 224kb, if another app crashes, no more heap memory will be added.;;;

column695:
2024-06-05 04:34;NLU3;Hi [~PMODILAY] thanks for your analysis and great suggestions, we will consider them in future updates.

Here is the design of diag_wd_monitor: [https://confluence.volvocars.biz/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=549208162], hopefully can be helpful for your understanding.

In my testing, I found the heap allocation only happened when the dir is /dev/shmem" and the allocation is inside the while loop:

 
{code:java}
DIR* dir = opendir("/dev/shmem"); // no heap allocation if the dir is not "/dev/shmem"
if (dir == nullptr)
{         
    return;     
}

struct dirent* dir_entry = readdir(dir);
while (dir_entry != nullptr)
{           
    dir_entry = readdir(dir); // no heap allocation if delete this line    
}
closedir(dir); {code}
So the heap allocation only happened when reading /dev/shmem dir through readdir, it had no relation to CopyFile process, because the trigger condition of file copy was not fulfilled(the persistent storage trigger happens when UsageModeConvinience changes to False and PlatformState changes to Failure).;;;

